#Breadth First Search

Explanation:
1. Definition
Breadth First Search (BFS) is a graph/tree traversal algorithm that visits nodes level by level.
It explores all neighboring nodes before moving to the next level.
2. Working
BFS starts from a source node.
It visits the node, marks it as visited, and adds its adjacent nodes to a queue.
3. Data Structure Used
BFS uses a Queue to maintain the order of nodes to be visited.
The first inserted node is processed first (FIFO).
4. Applications
Finding the shortest path in an unweighted graph.
Network broadcasting, web crawling, and level-order traversal of trees.

Algorithm:
a. Start from the source node.
b. Mark it as visited and enqueue it.
c. While the queue is not empty:
   - Dequeue a node.
   - Visit the node.
   - Enqueue all its unvisited adjacent nodes.
d. Repeat until the queue becomes empty.

#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 4
void breadth_first_search(int adj[][MAX],int visited[],int start)
{

int i,front=-1,rear=-1;
int queue[MAX];
queue[++rear] = start; //q[0]=0   rear=0
visited[start] = 1; //visited[0]=1
while(rear != front)
{
 start = queue[++front]; //start=q[1]=1  front=0 rear=0
 
 printf("%c \t",start+65);
	 	 for(i = 0; i < MAX; i++)//i=2
 {
	 	 	 if(adj[start][i] == 1 && visited[i] == 0) //adj[2][0]  visited[2]=0
 {
 queue[++rear] = i; //queue[3]= 1  rear=2
visited[i] = 1;  //visited[1]=1
 }
 }
}
}

int main()
{
	 int visited[MAX] = {0};
	 int adj[MAX][MAX], i, j;
printf("\n Enter the adjacency matrix: ");
	 for(i = 0; i < MAX; i++)
	 	 for(j = 0; j < MAX; j++)
 scanf("%d", &adj[i][j]);

breadth_first_search(adj,visited,0);
	 return 0;
}

